{
  "text": "28 LOXL1-LOXL4 are also capable of cross-linking collagen, but little is known about their expression in muscle. The LOXL1-LOXL4 family members have a conserved domain responsible for catalyzing the initial reaction in collagen cross-linking. Their distinct roles are not well understood, but LOXL2 has been shown to be upregulated in fibrotic tissue and responsible for collagen cross-linking in fibrosis. [CITATION_1] Our initial investigation showed that LOXL2 expression is not significantly altered in dystrophic muscle, providing supporting evidence for LOX being the primary enzyme responsible for crosslinking changes in dystrophic muscle. Critically, it is well established that cross-linked collagen is much less susceptible to turnover, [CITATION_2] thus implicating collagen cross-linking in the development of progressive scar tissue formation that predominates in muscles from DMD patients.",
